text: " Dunkirk" was --historically-- a retreat that allowed England to save it's finest soldiers from total annihilation by The Panzer's of Hitler's Wehrmacht. Both the French & British forces had been surrounded, & they faced total complete destruction. Because evacuation back across the channel DID work, & with it, Hitler lost his appetite for invasion, England was able --sort of, anyway--to catch it's breath, & prepare for a long struggle. In truth, Hitler's defeatist racism against the Slavic peoples of Eastern Europe & The USSR, set him up for the fateful / fatal, Operation Barbarossa. ---------------Wolfsky9

text: When the Nazi army over ran France in the summer of 1940, the retreating French & British armies were surrounded at the French western coast near the city of Dunkirk. The British organized a fleet of small boats. Many maned by civilians to rescue the troops and bring them across the English channel to the UK. About 330,000 British and French troops were rsscued, to fight another day. It would take almost 4 years for the allies to make a return invasion at Normandy.
author: David S

text: It' looks like it'll be great, but part of me wishes that If Nolan was going to make a WWII movie about the British that he picked a more interesting battle like Operation Compass or Crusader, The Second Battle of El Alamein, Slim's campaign's in Burma/India,  Operation Overlord etc. Not that I'm saying that Dunkirk isn't interesting, but that some of those other battles would make a more impressive spectacle on the big screen.   Though that being said, maybe Nolan could do something like The Human Condition Trilogy, were Nolan could make a saga about WWII that covers different stages of the British (and/or possibly other Allied) forces struggles during WWII. Like the second movie could be Operation Torch or El Alimein (something in the Western Desert Campaign) Then the Third movie could be Overlord and possibly the push into Germany.

text: these guys look too fresh, nonchalant,  clean, too well groomed and have pleasant looks on their faces. they had just fought hard all the way to the coast (with no escape from there!) while being pursued (fleeing for their lives) by a ruthless, well-equipped enemy that massively outnumbered them. sick to their stomachs of death at any moment, or a looming definitely losing massive battle and imprisonment in a POW camp for years. thankfully, Hitler was a believer in the occult and his 'reader' (our agent) told him that Dunkirk was too dangerous and not to attack us there. there was some very limited strafing and even some heavy bombing by the Luftwaffe that the RAF fought like lions against. unfortunately most of the airbattles were not fought within sight of the beaches causing the men there to wonder where the RAF was (and more than a few undeserved curses). Gen von Rundstedt was livid because he could have easily and completely annihilated all allied troops on Dunkirk but was not allowed to by the suspicious Hitler.  Churchill said this of Dunkirk - 'the events in France "a colossal military disaster", saying "the whole root and core and brain of the¬†British Army" had been stranded at Dunkirk and seemed about to perish or be captured.¬†In his¬†We shall fight on the beaches¬†speech on 4 June, he hailed their rescue as a "miracle of deliverance" ' The 'Miracle of Dunkirk' evacuation aka 'Operation Dynamo' lasted 10 gut clenching days.  Every English ship or boat capable of the journey did so. Many were suited for littoral waters only but crossed the Channel anyway. The First French army which had been reduced to a mere 40k men fought a blocking action this entire time. as a result, 338,226 men, mostly Brits but including Canadians, Ozzies, Kiwis, Polish, Belgians, Dutch and French were evacuated. on the last day, June 4th, 40k remaining French soldiers were captured. Bless every one of them because the math works out that they saved approx 10 men each. Vive la France!

text: THIS is how you make a trailer. These days trailers are far too long, give away too much of the story, and rarely raise any anticipation or curiosity about the movie.  Here, in just over a minute, Nolan has, without any spoken words, given us a location, a time, a feeling, an emotion, and made you want to know more. That final scene of the soldiers in the boat - first one soldier looks up at the sound of a diving plane, then a couple more look up, then as the sound of more planes come in, everyone looks up, and then they all react - is so expertly done that you don't even need to be shown what is going on in order to know what is going on.  That is some A Grade film-making right there. I can't wait to see this.

text: Do....do any of you understand the concept of an announcement trailer? The filming isn't anywhere near finished by this point. Teasers are designed to make the audience aware that this is a thing that's happening, and give them a small, spoiler free sneak preview of what lies ahead. Big faces are not likely to show up, no plot details will be revealed and THAT IS THE POINT!   As for the 1D fans complaining about Harry Styles not showing up in the trailer, get over it! He's likely not the focus of this film. If it is to be directed in a believable way, it will focus on the story of many different soldiers and the effect this event will have on them and perhaps even their families. Harry may be a big name in music, but he's really nothing in the acting world......yet, anyway. Perhaps this is a chance for him to prove himself as a pretty great actor, or maybe he'll just he a side character, or....well, who the hell knows? Just don't slag off this teaser simply because your "precious baby" didn't have his face in the spotlight. Jeez -.-

So to all the people saying "he only got the role because he's a famous singer" please stfu this is a serious movie with a serious director who will only want the best of the best actors to bring to life a tragic historical event that changed history. Christopher Nolan couldn't care less about Harry's music career, and neither should you, because him being a singer means nothing for this movie, it's his acting debut and his acting skills should not be judged by judgmental middle aged men who have some sort of problem with this generation, until we all actually see the movie and see what he can do.

text: For every man, woman,  who put their lives on the line and lost  them in our wars. For all of the countries that stood united against  these evils that threatend the safety and the freedom of our people..  For some of us, at that time, we were not divided, but stood together in  hand united. Not for any personal gain or personal power, but just  because it was the right thing to do....   At this time, in this  moment, lets give a thought to those who refused to back down. Who stood  up and said no, we will not lay down and let you destroy us. As our cities burned, we battled them on land, we battled them on waters, and our angels took to the sky....  They laid down a pathway so that you and I could become who we wanted to be.....   Deep down, we are all more alike than we think. I pray the world leaders  of these countries and their people remember.... remember,  that we once were united. - SHOGUNRONIN

The helmets in that scene I have just watched...all looking up...all look pristine, as if they had just been issued...ah well!!

text: Thank you for the hommage Mr. Nolan, my great uncle was a french infantry man stranded on that coast that made it on board. Watching the less fortunate whimpering and begging to get on¬†the overweight vessels longing to live to fight an other day changed his life. I am¬†looking forward to¬†get a glimpse of reality through those soldiers eyes, there confusion and misinformation that culminated¬†on the shores¬†of Calais, dazzled by two¬†consecutive lightning weeks. I trust you not to just scratch the surface but dig deep, as¬†noted in the trailer " survival is victory", a hint to a new¬†strategy of war¬†as¬†the wrath of a refined and¬†gracious weapon is reviled once more in its strategic-psychological¬†role, a phoenix revered as¬†The Luftwaffe.¬†In the shape of a loud black bird whirling down,¬†impacting the service man in a way that made my great uncle swear never to father children and caused a multitude of front line british to question their abilities and doubt themselves- a sense of German efficiency and supremacy only countered after Montgomeris defeat of Rommel. This Phoenix of technology and contemporary military thought faced its British contemporary, disconnected from the earthly chaos¬†by a sheet of clouds these british¬†pilots slapped the mighty bird (phonix) on the nose and thus founded the basis¬†fore the¬†Phoenix's return to dust.

text: So many stupid comments below about french being cowards or British running away etc etc. Everyone was caught out by naked German aggression in Poland. The allies weren't preparing for war, they were in appeasement mode so their armies were psychologically unprepared for Blitzkrieg. Dunkirk was an example of rescuing a disastrous situation and transforming it into a lucky escape through the courage of all arms of the services, in particular the navy and the French and British rearguard who enabled the operation. The airforce also played a significant role, far from the beaches breaking up German attacks as best they could. The royal navy took more casualties in the 9 days of the evacuation than the Australian navy took in the whole of WW2. Dynamo was a highly successful operation, which, in the circumstances was something of a miracle. The debacle that lead to it had many causes, not the least was the capitulation of Belgium without warning the allies thus completely exposing the entire British left flank and placing both it and French First Army in danger of encirclement. Huge weaknesses in allied strategy were exposed, but unlike the Germans, the allies learnt form their mistakes. Nazi barbarity would mean that Germany had to leave more than thirty divisions in France to repress resistance movements and the threat of British invasion. This meant that Barbarossa was doomed. Britain's ability to keep and maintain alliances by intervening on their behalf and demonstrating to the world that they were going to fight on meant that despite all Germany's military might it was destined to be one of the shortest lived Empires in history. Once the allies had learnt from the Germans their chief tactical tricks - (finger 4 formation in the air, use of massed rather than dispersed armour, airborne infantry, light bombers in close support of infantry operating as mobile artillery etc) the fight of WW2 though terrible was actually quite brief and totally conclusive. If Dunkirk proves anything it proves how totally dominant British rhetoric, propaganda and intelligence were compared to the Germans. Churchill managed to turn an embarrassing rout into one of Britain's finest hours. Someone mentioned Dresden below. I think saturation bombing was probably a mistake, for both moral and strategic reasons. Tactical use of heavy bombers would have had more impact than area bombing. But....... I do get a bit confused when Germans start getting shirty about it. If you sew the seed you reap the whirlwind. Or think of it as Karma-  when massed rallies in Germany were singing "We are bombing over England" and the German airwaves were gloating over the destruction wreaked on Rotterdam and London , the British were listening in. So it's not really reasonable to expect that people who've been attacked, humiliated, and blown up will behave in a generous and thoughtful manner. As the old saying goes - if you don't like the punishment don't commit the crime. The same goes for Japan who make quite a bit of moral mileage out the nuclear attacks. They were dreadful, awful acts of violence. But in 1945 allied forces had been fighting their way up through Asia discovering atrocity after atrocity committed by Japanese troops. Is it reasonable to expect people who've been brutalised to behave rationally? By and large the allies adhered to the conventions of war more closely than the axis powers. Japan was not even a signatory to the Geneva convention. Were the nuclear attacks morally correct - no. Were they understandable? Absolutely.

text: A beautiful movie certainly but also learn the truth about Dunkirk :  1) May 1940. The French, British and Belgian allied armies are stranded  by the Wehrmacht.  While French General Weygang is considering a counterattack, Lord Gort  (head of the British Expeditionary Corps) decides to withdraw to  England. Weygand agreed to cover the British  retreat "Operation Dynamo" organized from Dover by Churchill and Admiral  Ramsey ... from 24 to 26 May the exhausted Germans stopped their  advance, allowing the allies to form a corridor of withdrawal, and one  Perimeter of defense around Dunkerque.  2) 400,000 Allied soldiers were surrounded by 800,000 Germans. The  French and British navies are regrouping for the evacuation, on May 27  more than 10,000 British are evacuated. Marines  of war are supported by an armada of "Little Ships" coming from England  (519) from France (300) of the Netherlands (29) ... 28 May the king of  the Belgians Leopold III capitulates: decision strongly disputed by the  French and British.  3) On 29th May the general attack of the Germans began ... 30,000 French  soldiers, between  2,500 and 6,000 British, and 160,000 Germans were directly engaged in  the battle. The French defenses held firm, led by General Fagalde and  Admiral Abrial. But the British lines quickly disintegrated after the  first skirmishes. The  original order of Dover provided for full participation by the British  in the defense of Dunkirk, an order made evacuation a top priority.  4) Only the Royal Air Force will participate actively in the battle  alongside French  aviation, in an interview with Fagalde and Abrial, British General  Alexander confirms that he can not hire his troops, he adds that "anyway  his men Are tired "... Abrial answers that the  mission will be ensured by the French troops alone by the words" we are  linked to an imperative mission that is to resist until death to save  all the possible French and English personnel of  The bridgehead of  Dunkerque, as long as this goal has not been reached, we will remain  there "  5) The Tommies then pile up on the beaches, waiting for their evacuation  ... Fagalde  manages to reorganize the defensive device before the Germans take  advantage of the gaping hole caused by the British withdrawal.  Meanwhile,  in the sector of Lilles, 2 heteroclite divisions of the 1st French  Army, commanded by General Molini√©, contain 7 German divisions ...  including 3 elite armored divisions, commanded by General Rommel ... 28  to 31 May this fierce resistance prevents German reinforcements from  advancing towards the coast. In his memoirs of wars W Churchill writes:  Molinie's epic resistance allowed him to evacuate 100000 more men.  6) 30 May: the fighting is now taking place in the heart of Dunkerque,  the city is  under the continuous fire of the German artillery and the Lutwaffe, the  French hold their positions (writes American historian W. Lord)                                                                   Goerg Von  K√ºchler, who commanded the 18th Army of the Whermacht, writes in  his war diary: "Despite our overwhelming enumeric and material  superiority, the French counterattack in several places, I do not  understand how these struggling soldiers sometimes have 1 against 20,  find the strength to storm. It's amazing.  7) I find in these French soldiers the same enthusiasm as those of  Verdun in 1916, we do  not pierce anywhere and undergo terrifying losses ... with this  extraordinary French resistance, the evacuations reach a peak of  efficiency during these terrible days. On 2 June the last British  soldiers were evacuated. On  the same day, General Janssen, commander of the 12th DMI, died in  battle, which repulsed numerous German assaults from Fort Des Dunes.  Showing an unprecedented heroism, reports a German officer.  8) The last evacuations under the direct pressure of the Whermacht, are  made in  an indescribable chaos ... Fagalde Abrial and the Admiral Platon are  among the last convoys which arrive "in extremis" to cross. On 4 June  the last allied ship leaves Dunkirk around 3:45  am. At 10 o'clock the fighting ceased.  9) 35,000 French soldiers who have sacrificed themselves fighting to the  end are  taken prisoner ... Churchill and Ramsey estimated that a maximum of  40000 soldiers could be evacuated during Operation Dynamo ... in the  end it is 198000 men, Almost all of the British professional soldiers,  including the future marshals Alexander and Montgomery who were  repatriated. 140000 French and Belgian were also repatriated, a total of  238226 men. The Royal Navy, which transported 2/3 of the men, lost 112  ships in the operation; The French Navy 123 ships.  10) The city of Dunkerque is destroyed to 90%. There are more than 3000  civilian deaths and 10000 injuries. In 9 days of fighting the allies  lost 18219 men including 16000 French. Operation Dynamo, however, is  considered a victory in Britain. Rescued from Dunkerque, Lieutenant  Bourl√®s of 71√®m RI recounts his passage in England: Having covered the  British embarkation, we were considered  heroes, young people asked for autographs, the officers greeted us with  gratitude.  11) In the hours that follow most of the French soldiers is sent back to  Brest and  Cherbourg in order to continue the battle of France against Germany and  Italy. During these violent clashes Germany lost 160000 men  (as much as during the Normandy campaign in 1944) 1800 German tanks  were destroyed or damaged, and the Lutwaffe lost 50% of its forces,  consequently the Reich would be very weak in the forces In the Battle of  Britain. For  British general Allan Brook: "difficult to imagine how England could  have continued the war without Dunkirk" ... For Walter Lord the battle  of Dunkirk is the turning point of the 2nd World War  12) England defeated, Germany could have turned all these forces towards  Russia, Stalingrad and D-Day would not have taken place. "Dunkirk was a  disaster for Germany" Von Kl√ºcher writes: "Dunkirk is a defeat  for us: practically all the British expeditionary force escaped us  because of a few thousand brave French soldiers who blocked us Dunkirk  brings me the evidence that the French soldier is one of the best in  the world ... resisting for 10 days our forces far superior in number,  the French army has probably saved the Great Britain's defeat enabling  its professional army to join the British side  13) In the aftermath of Operation Dynamo British propaganda will invent  the myth of  the "Dunkirk spirit" touting the courage of the Tommies in adversity,  the English media will speak with emphasis of the "miracle of  Dunkerque", but there was no Miracle, only the courage and the  formidable aptitude to fight of these forgotten French soldiers...
